## **Conclusion: Synthesizing the Narrative of Reinforced Dependence**

The strength of the proposed story lies in its rejection of a single-cause explanation. It correctly identifies that the path to independence is not just "blocked," but is being actively "de-constructed" by a variety of reinforcing economic factors. The decline in licensure 2 is not just a trend; it is a response to the "skyrocketing" cost of insurance 9 and the reality that most teens are "at the end of the hiring queue" due to rising employer expectations and minimum wage dynamics.7

For a journalist like Andrew Van Dam or Ben Casselman, the "main chart" would be the point of departure for an investigation into why "The Opt-Out Revolution" for mothers has transitioned into a "Stretched to the Limit" reality for the entire family.35 By selecting journalists who understand the "massive forces pulling at the economy like tides," the feature will move beyond generational tropes and provide a rigorous, data-driven autopsy of the American "rite of passage" in the 21st century.19

